node.text: Creative Visionary @jeffstaple joins us live in store at Stadium Goods NYC to talk all things from Staple to Hiphop. Hosted by @frescobk

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear.

node.text: Rather than reinterpreting an existing colorway of the Air Jordan 4, Union modifies the shoe with a stitched down tongue and mesh and suede construction on the "Taupe Haze” colorway celebrating the LA-based shop's 30th anniversary.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods on August 15, 2021. May be an image of footwear.

node.text: Jordan Brand took a different approach to a Halloween colorway on this women’s edition of the Air Jordan 1 High Zoom CMFT. Sans ghouls and goblins graphics, the “Lemon Venom” opts for a black-and-purple vibe that suggests Halloween more subtly.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear.

node.text: Kanye West’s perfectionist mentality impacts his music… and his adidas Yeezys, too. His Yeezy 450 had been in the works for years before it debuted in February. Like everything else ‘Ye takes his time crafting, the 450 was worth the wait.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods.

node.text: We can’t blame you for wearing the adidas Yeezy Foam Runner without socks during the dog days of summer. But when the weather cools down, our “Biome” Stadium Goods Crew Sock Pack has your sock needs covered with options that match the comfy footwear style.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear.

node.text: The Nike Dunk’s original two-tone color block will forever be a timeless look for the vintage basketball shoe. Here, Nike adheres to the two-color combination on the women’s exclusive “Football Grey” from January 2021.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear and text that says 'NIKE'.

node.text: How similar are the Air Jordan 1 and the Nike Dunk? Both were designed by Peter Moore and released in 1985. And now, the styles share a similar colorway thanks to the new Jordan 1 “Pollen,” which mimics the color block of the Dunk’s “Iowa” design.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear.

node.text: The bond between women in and out of sneaker culture is the reason the cotton rope lacing appears between the panels on the Women’s Air Jordan 1 Mid “Sisterhood.” File this one as another creative look for the boundary-pushing shoe.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear.

node.text: A fresh patch of botanical themed Nike Air Force 1s headline a selection of women’s exclusive colorways for shoe's Summer 2021 campaign. Seen here is the “Catechu,” which looks to India’s acacia tree of the same name for design inspiration.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear.

node.text: There’s no denying the adidas Yeezy Boost 700 “Wave Runner’s” impact. Introduced in 2017, the shoe with retro-inspired details opened the door to the ""dad shoe"" movement that still permeates through sneaker culture.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear and shorts.

node.text: Effortless summer style begins with the classics. For a clean vibe, pair the Air Jordan 1 Low OG “Neutral Grey” with options from our Stadium Goods “Blues” sock collection and BAPE’s comfortable shorts.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear.

node.text: If it ain’t broke, don’t fix it. The Air Jordan 1 Low “Game Royal” continues the model’s association with “Royal,” an original color option on the first edition of Michael Jordan’s signature shoe from 1985.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Stadium Goods in Stadium Goods. May be an image of footwear.

node.text: Without saying as much, the multiple camouflage patterns found on the Nike Dunk Low “Sail/Multi-Camo” slyly reference the brand’s “What The” theme that has appeared on countless Nike releases in the past.
